discussion of units.

00:05:07.480 --> 00:05:10.970
And that will become
interesting and important later

00:05:10.970 --> 00:05:14.070
on when we look at
particle physics examples.

00:05:14.070 --> 00:05:15.740
So in particle
physics, we often talk

00:05:15.740 --> 00:05:19.040
about units of electronvolt
in collision experiments,

00:05:19.040 --> 00:05:22.700
or mega electronvolts,
or kilo electronvolts,

00:05:22.700 --> 00:05:24.320
tera electronvolts.

00:05:24.320 --> 00:05:27.980
So 1 electronvolt is
the kinetic energy

00:05:27.980 --> 00:05:34.010
of the particle with charge
e, which is accelerated

00:05:34.010 --> 00:05:38.060
in a potential of 1 volts.

00:05:38.060 --> 00:05:40.480
So that corresponds--
that's a unit of energy

00:05:40.480 --> 00:05:42.350
and it corresponds
to 1.6 times 10

00:05:42.350 --> 00:05:45.583
to the minus 19
joules or 1.6 times 10

00:05:45.583 --> 00:05:50.160
to the minus 90 kilograms
meter squared over 2nd square.

00:05:50.160 --> 00:05:54.120
But the mass of an electron
is really, really small.

00:05:54.120 --> 00:05:56.340
And those units
here are introduced

00:05:56.340 --> 00:05:58.170
because the mass
is small and you

00:05:58.170 --> 00:06:00.840
want to have reasonable
numbers to work with.

00:06:00.840 --> 00:06:04.110
So the mass of the
electron is 9.11 times

00:06:04.110 --> 00:06:06.240
10 to the minus 31 kilogram.

00:06:08.910 --> 00:06:13.620
So if you just rewrite an m0 as
equal to m0 c squared times 1

00:06:13.620 --> 00:06:16.170
over c squared you
find that, huh,

00:06:16.170 --> 00:06:21.460
now we rewrite this and find
that the masses 8 times 10

00:06:21.460 --> 00:06:25.450
to the minus 14
joules over c squared.

00:06:25.450 --> 00:06:28.320
Or in units of
electronvolts, 5 times 10

00:06:28.320 --> 00:06:31.600
to the 5 electronvolts
over c squared,

00:06:31.600 --> 00:06:35.670
which is 0.511 mega
electronvolts over c squared

00:06:35.670 --> 00:06:39.950
or 511 kilo electrons
over c squared.

00:06:39.950 --> 00:06:42.640
So when we talk about
the mass of an electron,

00:06:42.640 --> 00:06:46.080
we sometimes approach this
with natural units, in which c

00:06:46.080 --> 00:06:47.800
squared is equal to 1.

00:06:47.800 --> 00:06:52.270
And that just simply says
that the mass of an electron

00:06:52.270 --> 00:06:55.870
is 511 kilo electronvolts.

